  <h2>Maize's Market: Top-Rated Schools Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>Maize is in Sedgwick County northwest of Wichita. Small city proper (about 4,500), but the USD 266 Maize school district serves a much larger area and is one of the top-rated in Kansas. That school reputation is the core of Maize's market. Families move here specifically for the schools. That creates stability and consistent buyer demand — when a good home comes on the market in Maize, people notice because they're coming here for education.</p>
  <p>You get a mix of 1980s-1990s established ranches and significant new construction. Price range is $180k-$320k. When Maize homeowners sell, it's often because they're upgrading to bigger homes to grow their families, or their life changed and they need fast liquidity.</p>

  <h2>Maize Housing Stock and Market</h2>
  <p>Maize is mostly 1980s-1990s established ranch homes mixed with newer construction from 1990s forward as the district grows. USD 266 is the draw — consistently top-rated, families buy Maize specifically for school access. Price range is $180k-$320k. Homes are generally well-maintained because family-oriented school districts attract people who care about their neighborhoods.</p>
  <p>The school district reputation is so strong that it can sometimes create a seller's advantage — demand is steady and buyer pool is large. But when people need to sell fast, they need someone who moves at their pace.</p>

  <h2>Who I Buy From in Maize</h2>
  <p>Families upgrading to larger homes for growing kids — most common. They bought a 3-bedroom, now they have three kids and need four-bedroom, but they need to sell the old house fast so they can buy bigger. Relocations for job changes. Divorces in family-oriented areas — assets need to be liquidated quickly. People who moved to Maize for the schools, situation changed (job transfer, family situation), and they need out. Estate sales from original Maize buyers aging out.</p>

